# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: eliot-chapple
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:eliot-chapple/american-anthropological-association] The **American Anthropological Association** (**AAA**) is an American organization of scholars and practitioners in the field of anthropology.
[src:eliot-chapple/american-anthropological-association] The AAA publishes more than 20 peer-reviewed scholarly journals, available in print and online through AnthroSource.
[src:eliot-chapple/american-anthropological-association] The first anthropological society in the US was the American Ethnological Society of New York, which was founded by Albert Gallatin and revived in 1899 by Franz Boas after a hiatus.
[src:eliot-chapple/american-anthropological-association] 1879 saw the establishment of the Anthropological Society of Washington (which first published the journal *American Anthropologist*, before it became a national journal), and 1882 saw the American Association for the Advancement of Science established an anthropological section.
[src:eliot-chapple/american-anthropological-association] Boas and other anthropologist discussed the possibility of creating a single national society already in 1898, but fears that it might damage the AAAS caused a long discussion.
[src:eliot-chapple/american-anthropological-association] In 1901 the AES and ASW sent members to attend the meeting of the AAAS anthropologists in Chicago in which discussions continued and there was general agreement that a national society should be formed.
[src:eliot-chapple/american-anthropological-association] Boas advocated a restricted membership of 40 "professional anthropologists", but the AAA's first president, W.
[src:eliot-chapple/american-anthropological-association] McGee, ensured that membership would be open to everyone with an interest in the discipline.
[src:eliot-chapple/american-anthropological-association] At its incorporation, it assumed responsibility for the journal*American Anthropologist*, created in 1888 by the Anthropological Society of Washington (ASW).
[src:eliot-chapple/american-anthropological-association] Business affairs are conducted by a 41-member Section Assembly representing each of the association's constituent sections, and a 15-member Executive Board.
[src:eliot-chapple/american-anthropological-association] From an initial membership of 175, the AAA grew slowly during the first half of the 20th century.
[src:eliot-chapple/american-anthropological-association] Annual meetings were held primarily in the Northeast and accommodated all attendees in a single room.
[src:eliot-chapple/american-anthropological-association] The offices of the AAA are located in Arlington, Virginia.
[src:eliot-chapple/american-anthropological-association] The AAA is composed of 40 sections, which are groups organized around identity affiliations or intellectual interests within the discipline of anthropology.
[src:eliot-chapple/american-anthropological-association] Sections each have an elected president or chair; many publish journals and host meetings.
[src:eliot-chapple/american-anthropological-association] The AAA publishes more than 20 section publications including *American Anthropologist*, *American Ethnologist*, *Cultural Anthropology*, *Anthropology & Education Quarterly* and *Medical Anthropology Quarterly*.
[src:eliot-chapple/american-anthropological-association] The AAA's official magazine, *Anthropology News*, is published bimonthly.
[src:eliot-chapple/american-anthropological-association] AAA publications are available online through AnthroSource.
[src:eliot-chapple/american-anthropological-association] Since 2007, journals have been published in partnership with Wiley-Blackwell since 2007.
[src:eliot-chapple/american-anthropological-association] Since 1962 the association has published the AAA AnthroGuide, giving staff and program information about anthropology departments.
[src:eliot-chapple/american-anthropological-association] Other issues addressed from the 1970s through the 1980s included illegal antiquities trade, the insertion of religious beliefs into social science texts, the preservation of endangered nonhuman primates, and the religious significance of peyote to Native Americans.
[src:eliot-chapple/american-anthropological-association] In 2004, in response to President George W.
[src:eliot-chapple/american-anthropological-association] Bush's call for a constitutional amendment banning same-sex marriage, the Association issued a statement on marriage and the family.
[src:eliot-chapple/american-anthropological-association] The Association also has adopted resolutions against the 2003 invasion of Iraq, against the use of anthropological knowledge as an element for physical or psychological torture, and against any covert or overt U.S. military action against Iran.
[src:eliot-chapple/american-anthropological-association] Following a referendum in 2023, the Association endorsed a boycott of Israeli academic institutions, joining the BDS movement.
[src:eliot-chapple/american-anthropological-association] A number of ideologically polarized debates within the discipline of anthropology have prompted the association to conduct investigations.
[src:eliot-chapple/american-anthropological-association] These include the dispute between Derek Freeman and defenders of Margaret Mead, as well as the controversy over the book *Darkness in El Dorado*.
[src:eliot-chapple/american-anthropological-association] The AAA has issued a number of statements on the topic of race, and since the 1950s has argued publicly that race is best understood as a cultural or bio-cultural rather than mostly biological construction.
[src:eliot-chapple/american-anthropological-association] In 2006, the association developed and continues to manage a public education program titled "RACE: Are We So Different?" The program includes a traveling museum exhibit, an interactive website, and educational materials.
[src:eliot-chapple/american-anthropological-association] Initially, AAA was highly skeptical of the concept of universal human rights, with some anthropologists arguing that because of cultural relativism there are no principles that can be universally valid for humans of all cultures.
[src:eliot-chapple/american-anthropological-association] IN 1947 the AAA issued a statement on Human rights, noting that value judgments are culturally contextual and arguing that a declaration about universal human rights ought to take into consideration and encompass all the different human value systems.
[src:eliot-chapple/american-anthropological-association] This stance has gradually been abandoned by most anthropologists, many of whom today see universal human rights as an important way through which discrimination and oppression of cultural minorities can be reduced.
[src:eliot-chapple/american-anthropological-association] District Court in Arizona entered a permanent injunction barring enforcement of the remaining provisions.
[src:eliot-chapple/american-anthropological-association] With the law's repeal, AAA's ban on considering AAA conferences in Arizona was lifted.
[src:eliot-chapple/american-anthropological-association] Through 2007 and 2008, debates surrounding anthropologists and the military resurfaced in response to the Pentagon's Human Terrain System (HTS) project.
[src:eliot-chapple/american-anthropological-association] Following a number of national news articles on the project, anthropologists began to debate the project and related ethical issues.
[src:eliot-chapple/american-anthropological-association] Proponents of the program argued that anthropologists were providing much-needed cultural knowledge about local populations and helping to decrease violence in their areas of operation.
[src:eliot-chapple/american-anthropological-association] Critics, however, argued that HTS anthropologists could not receive informed consent from their research subjects in a war zone and that information provided by anthropologists might put populations in danger.
[src:eliot-chapple/american-anthropological-association] To address these issues, the Association's Executive Board released a statement on 31 October 2007.
[src:eliot-chapple/american-anthropological-association] It cited "sufficiently troubling and urgent ethical issues" raised by the project, including the difficulties for HTS anthropologists to receive informed consent without coercion from their research subjects and to uphold their ethical mandate to "do no harm" to those they study.
[src:eliot-chapple/american-anthropological-association] The AAA urged members to adhere to its code of ethics, which outlines principles and guidelines for ethical behavior.
[src:eliot-chapple/american-anthropological-association] However, the association does not adjudicate cases involving charges of unethical behavior or bar members from participating in the HTS program.
[src:eliot-chapple/american-anthropological-association] In addition, the Association's Commission on the Engagement of Anthropology with US Security and Intelligence Communities (CEAUSSIC) issued a final report released during the AAA's 2007 annual meeting, based on over a year of work.
[src:eliot-chapple/american-anthropological-association] It neither endorsed nor condemned anthropological work with military, intelligence and security organizations, but instead outlined the opportunities and challenges of working in these sectors.
[src:eliot-chapple/american-anthropological-association] Opposition to military cooperation was evident during that meeting.
[src:eliot-chapple/american-anthropological-association] Some critics of the HTS program have suggested that scholars who perform classified work with the military be expelled from the organization.
[src:eliot-chapple/american-anthropological-association] During an event organized by the Network of Concerned Anthropologists, a graduate student who had recently been expelled from the HTS program spoke out about her experiences.
[src:eliot-chapple/american-anthropological-association] She argued that the program was poorly run but was doing positive work in helping military officers with "nation-building" activities.
[src:eliot-chapple/american-anthropological-association] Until August 2007, AnthroSource was a collaboration between the University of California Press and the Association.
[src:eliot-chapple/american-anthropological-association] It, along with all their journals, has since been removed from the University of California Press by the AAA Board and transferred to Wiley-Blackwell.
[src:eliot-chapple/american-anthropological-association] Commencing 2008, AnthroSource was to be hosted and managed by Wiley-Blackwell as part of the five-year publishing contract awarded.
[src:eliot-chapple/american-anthropological-association] AAA presidents have been drawn from all of the four subdisciplines of American anthropology: Until 2003 the presidents counted 46 socio-cultural anthropologists, 19 archeologists, six physical anthropologists and six linguists.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] Born in Wakefield, Massachusetts, Coon became interested in anthropology after attending Earnest Hooton's lectures at Harvard University.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] He obtained his PhD in 1928 based on an ethnographic study of the Rif Berbers of Morocco.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] Returning to Harvard as a lecturer, he conducted further fieldwork in the Balkans, North Africa, and the Middle East.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] In 1948 he was appointed a professor of anthropology at the University of Pennsylvania and remained there until his retirement in 1963, also serving as the Curator of Ethnology at the Penn Museum.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] During World War II, he was an agent for the Office of Strategic Services (OSS), where he used his anthropological fieldwork as a cover for an arms-smuggling operation in Vichy France-controlled Morocco.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] He was awarded the Legion of Merit and after the war he retained ties to the military and the OSS's successor, the Central Intelligence Agency.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] He wrote about his wartime experiences in his book, *A North Africa Story: The Anthropologist as OSS Agent* (1980).
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] Coon's early work in physical anthropology, such as *The Races of Europe* (1939), was typical of its time.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] He described the different racial 'types' supposedly present in human populations, but rejected a specific definition of 'race' and made no attempt to explain how these types arose.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] This changed after 1950, as Coon attempted to defend an essentialist concept of race against the new physical anthropology of contemporaries such as Sherwood Washburn and Ashley Montagu, who argued that the emerging understanding of human genetics negated race as a scientific category.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] In *The Origins of Races* (1962), Coon set forth his theory that there were five distinct subspecies of *Homo sapiens* that evolved in parallel in different parts of the world, and that some had evolved further than others.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] The book was widely castigated upon its publication and marked a decisive break between Coon and the scientific mainstream.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] He resigned the American Association of Physical Anthropologists in 1961, after it voted to condemn a white supremacist book written by Coon's cousin Carleton Putnam.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] Though Coon continued to defend his theories until his death and rejected the accusations that he was a racist, they were quickly excluded from the scientific consensus as "outmoded ..., typological and racist".
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] Aside from physical anthropology, Coon conducted a series of archaeological excavations of Stone Age cave sites in Iran, Afghanistan and Syria.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] These included Bisitun Cave, where he discovered traces of the Neanderthals, and Hotu cave, which he claimed showed evidence of early agriculture, though subsequent excavations proved this false.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] He was also a lifelong proponent of the existence of cryptid 'Wild Men' such as the Sasquatch and Yeti, which he believed were relict populations of human-like apes that, when found, would support his theory of the separate origins of human races.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] He was involved in planning 'Yeti-hunting' expeditions to Nepal and Tibet, though it has also been speculated that these were cover for espionage.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] Coon was married twice, first to Mary Goodale and then to Lisa Dougherty Geddes.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] Coon Jr., a diplomat who served as the American Ambassador to Nepal.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] Carleton Stevens Coon was born in Wakefield, Massachusetts on June 23, 1904.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] His parents were John Lewis Coon, a cotton factor, and Bessie Carleton.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] His family had Cornish American roots and two of his ancestors fought in the American Civil War.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] As a child, he listened to his grandfather's stories of the war and of traveling in the Middle East, and accompanied his father on business trips to Egypt, inspiring an early interest in Egyptology.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] He initially attended Wakefield High School, but was expelled after breaking a water pipe and flooding the school's basement, after which he went to Phillips Academy.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] Coon was a precocious student, learning to read Egyptian hieroglyphs at an early age and excelling at Ancient Greek.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] Wakefield was an affluent and almost exclusively white town.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] Howells, noted that his "only apparent awareness of ethnicity" was in childhood fights with his Irish American neighbours.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] Intending to study Egyptology, Coon enrolled at Harvard University and was able to obtain a place on a graduate course with George Andrew Reisner based on his knowledge of hieroglyphic.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] He also studied Arabic and English composition under Charles Townsend Copeland.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] However he changed his focus to anthropology after taking a course with Earnest Hooton, inspired by his lectures on the Berbers of the Moroccan Rif.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] Coon obtained his bachelor's degree from Harvard in 1925 and immediately embarked on graduate studies in anthropology.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] He conducted his dissertation fieldwork in the Rif in 1925, which was politically unsettled after a rebellion of the local populace against the Spanish, and was awarded his PhD in 1928.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] Coon was motivated to study the Rif by the puzzle of the "light-skinned" Riffians' presence in Africa.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] Throughout much of his fieldwork, he relied on his local informant Mohammed Limnibhy, and even arranged for Limnibhy to live with him in Cambridge from 1928 to 1929.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] After obtaining his PhD, Coon returned to Harvard as a lecturer and later a professor.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] In 1931 he published his dissertation as the "definitive monograph" of the Rif Berber; studied Albanians from 1920 to 1930; traveled to Ethiopia in 1933; and in worked in Arabia, North Africa and the Balkans from 1925 to 1939.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] Coon left Harvard to take up a position at the University of Pennsylvania in 1948.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] Throughout the 1950s he produced academic papers, as well as many popular books for the general reader, notably including *The Story of Man* (1954).
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] During his years at Penn in the 1950s, he sometimes appeared on the television program called *What in the World?*, a game-show produced by the Penn Museum, and hosted by its director, Froelich Rainey, in which a panel of experts tried to identify an object in the museum's collection.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] He was awarded the Legion of Merit for his wartime services and the Viking Medal in Physical Anthropology in 1952.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] He was also named a Membre D'Honneur of the Association de la Libération française du 8 novembre 1942.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] From 1948 to the early 1960s, he was the Curator of Ethnology at the University Museum of Philadelphia.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] Coon wrote widely for a general audience like his mentor Earnest Hooton.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] Coon published *The Riffians*, *Flesh of the Wild Ox*, *Measuring Ethiopia*, and *A North Africa Story: The Anthropologist as OSS Agent*.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] *A North Africa Story* was an account of his work in North Africa during World War II, which involved espionage and the smuggling of arms to French resistance groups in German-occupied Morocco under the guise of anthropological fieldwork.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] During that time, Coon was affiliated with the United States Office of Strategic Services, the forerunner to the Central Intelligence Agency (CIA).
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] Coon served as a mentor to Lloyd Cabot Briggs, another Harvard-educated OSS agent and anthropologist, who embraced anthropometry (measuring features of the human body such as crania and nose sizes) as a means of asserting racial types and categories.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] Briggs wrote books such as *Living Races of the Sahara Desert* (1958) and *No More for Ever: A Saharan Jewish Town* (1962).
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] Historian Sarah Abrevaya Stein notes that Briggs and Coon corresponded during the writing of the latter, for example joking about the genital hair removal customs of Jewish women in Ghardaïa.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] After the war, Coon returned to Harvard.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] He wrote an influential paper in 1945 arguing that the U.S. should continue the use of wartime intelligence agencies to maintain an "Invisible Empire" in the postwar period.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] He served as a scientific consultant to the CIA from 1948 to 1950 and from 1956 to 1957, worked as a photographer for the Air Force.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] Before World War II, Coon's work on race "fit comfortably into the old physical anthropology", describing the racial types supposedly present in human populations based on visible physical characteristics.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] He explicitly rejected any specific definition of race and used the concept to describe both highly specific groupings of people and continent-spanning racial types.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] In *The Races of Europe* (1939), for example, an update of William Z.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] In these early works Coon alluded to essential, "pure" racial types that produced the specific races he observed through hybridization, but did not attempt to explain how or where these types arose.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] He also posited that historically "different strains in one population have showed differential survival values and often one has reemerged at the expense of others (in Europeans)".
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] He suggested that the "maximum survival" of the European racial type was increased by the replacement of the indigenous peoples of the New World and stated that the history of the white race to involved "racial survivals" of white subraces.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] The immediate post-war period marked a decisive break in Coon's work on race as the conventional, typological approach was challenged by the "new physical anthropology".
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] Led by Coon's former classmate Sherwood Washburn, this was a movement to shift the field away from description and classification and towards an understanding of human variability grounded in the modern synthesis of biological evolution and population genetics.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] For some anthropologists, including Ashley Montagu and later Washburn himself, the new physical anthropology necessitated the wholesale rejection of race as a scientific category.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] In contrast, in *Races: A Study in the Problem of Race Formation in Man* (1950), Coon, together with his former student Stanley Garn and Joseph Birdsell, attempted to reconcile the race concept with the new physical anthropology's emphasis on genetics and adaptation.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] In 1962, Coon published his *The Origin of Races*, which advances his incorrect theories of the origins of essential racial types.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] He modified Franz Weidenreich's polycentric (or multiregional) theory of the origin of races, which states that human races evolved independently in the Old World from *Homo erectus* to *Homo sapiens sapiens* (although Weidenreich incorporated gene flow between populations).
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] Coon held that besides *H. erectus*, five subspecies each lived "in its own territory, [passing] a critical threshold from a more brutal to a more *sapient* state".
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] His form of polygenism is referred to by some as the Candelabra Hypothesis due to its lack of concern for gene flow.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] Coon suggested that the racial groups demonstrated the advance of civilization, for instance the Mongoloids and Caucasoids adapting to overcrowding by means of an evolved endocrine system.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] Coon also claimed that racial types sometimes annihilated others, while in other cases warfare and/or settlement led to their partial displacement.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] He asserted that Europe was the refined product of many years of racial progression.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] Coon's understanding of racial typology and diversity within the Indian sub-continent changed over time.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] As for the north of the sub-continent, it was an extension of the Caucasoid range.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] In short, the Indian sub-continent (North and South) is "the easternmost outpost of the Caucasoid racial region".
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] Underlying all of this was Coon's typological view of human history and biological variation, a way of thinking that is not taken seriously today by most anthropologists or biologists.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] The Civil Rights Movement of the 1960s and changing social attitudes challenged racial theories like Coon's that had been used by segregationists to justify discrimination and depriving people of civil rights.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] In 1961, Coon's distant cousin Carleton Putnam, wrote *Race and Reason: A Yankee View*, arguing a scientific basis for white supremacy and the continuation of racial segregation in the U.S.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] After the book was made required reading for high-school students in Louisiana, the American Association of Physical Anthropologists (AAPA) passed a resolution condemning it.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] Coon, who had corresponded with Putnam about the book as he was writing it and chaired the meeting of the AAPA in which the resolution was passed, resigned in protest, criticizing the resolution as scientifically irresponsible and a violation of free speech.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] Later, he claimed to have asked how many of those present at the meeting had read the book and that only one hand was raised.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] Coon published *The Origin of Races* in 1962.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] In its "Introduction", he described the book as part of the outcome of his project he conceived (in light of his work on *The Races of Europe*) around the end of 1956, for a work to be titled along the lines of *Races of the World*.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] He said that since 1959 he had proceeded with the intention to follow *The Origin of Races* with a sequel, so the two would jointly fulfill the goals of the original project.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] (He published *The Living Races of Man* in 1965.) The book asserted that the human species divided into five races before it had evolved into *H. sapiens*.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] Further, he suggested that the races evolved into *H. sapiens* at different times.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] The field of anthropology was moving rapidly from theories of race typology, and *The Origin of Races* was widely castigated by his peers in anthropology as supporting racist ideas with outmoded theory and notions which had long since been repudiated by modern science.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] One of his harshest critics, Theodosius Dobzhansky, scorned it as providing "grist for racist mills".
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] The dispute that followed the publication of *The Origin of Races* was personal as well as academic.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] Coon had known Ashley Montagu and Dobzhansky for decades and the three men often corresponded and wrote positive reviews of each other's work before 1962.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] Their vociferous criticism of *Origins* severed their friendship and affected Coon on a personal and emotional level.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] In a letter to Dobzhansky shortly after its publication, Coon advised him that he considered his critiques defamatory and had consulted a lawyer, writing: "Why have you done this?
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] When are you going to stop?" Washburn was a fellow student of Earnest Hooton at Harvard, and Coon saw his subsequent repudiation of biological race as an "oedipal" betrayal of their mentor.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] Garn, Coon's former student and coauthor of *Races*, helped draft the AAPA motion condemning Putnam, which also disappointed Coon.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] Coon stopped referencing Montagu and then Washburn in his work after they each publicly rejected the concept of race.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] Nevertheless, historian Peter Sachs Collopy has noted that Coon was able to maintain cordial relationships with many of those he had disagreements with, rooted in his belief in the importance of academic collegiality.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] Although some of these interpersonal conflicts faded over time—Coon wrote that he had "buried the now-rusty hatchet" with Dobzhansky in a letter to him in 1975—the animosity between Coon and Montagu was severe and lasting.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] Before 1962, the two were on friendly terms, but represented rival schools of anthropology (Coon studied under Hooton at Harvard; Montagu under Boas at Columbia), and Coon privately disdained his work.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] After the publication of *Origins*, they engaged in a lengthy correspondence, published in *Current Anthropology*, that "consisted almost entirely of bickering over minutiae, name calling, and sarcasm".
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] Privately, Coon suspected Montagu (a target of McCarthyism) of communist sympathies and of turning Dobzhansky and others against him.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] As late as 1977, he was quoted as saying to a colleague, "You had Ashley Montagu in your office?
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] Coon continued to write and defend his work until his death, publishing two volumes of memoirs in 1980 and 1981.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] After taking up his position at Pennsylvania in 1948, Coon embarked on a series of archaeological expeditions to Iran, Afghanistan and Syria.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] His 1949 excavations at four cave sites in Iran (Bisitun, Tamtama, Khunik and Belt) were the first systematic investigations of Palaeolithic archaeology in Iran.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] The most significant of these was Bisitun, which Coon called "Hunter's Cave", where he discovered evidence of the Mousterian industry and several human fossils that were later confirmed to belong to Neanderthals.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] Coon published the results of these excavations in a 1951 monograph, *Cave Explorations in Iran, 1949*, and subsequently wrote a popular book about the expeditions, *The Seven Caves: Archaeological Explorations in the Middle East* (1957).
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] Bisitun remained the only fully-published Palaeolithic site from Iran for several decades.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] Coon followed up his 1949 expedition with excavations at Hotu Cave in 1951.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] He interpreted the site, together with Belt Cave, as the first traces of a "Mesolithic" in Iran and claimed that they showed evidence of early agriculture.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] Other archaeologists questioned the basis for these claims and subsequent excavations at sites such as Ganj Dareh clarified that Coon had probably conflated separate Epipalaeolithic hunter-gatherer and Neolithic farmer occupations at the sites.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] Coon was, up to his death, a proponent of the existence of bipedal cryptids, including Sasquatch and Yeti.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] His 1954 book *The Story of Man* included a chapter on "Giant Apes and Snowmen" and a figure showing the purported footprints of an "Abominable Snowman" alongside those of extinct hominids, and near the end of his life he wrote a paper on "Why There Has to Be a Sasquatch".
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] In the late 1950s, he was approached by *Life* magazine about either joining Tom Slick and Peter Byrne's expedition to the Himalayas to search for evidence of Yeti, or organising his own expedition.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] Although Coon spent some time planning the logistics, in the end neither materialised.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] Coon believed that cryptid "Wild Men" were relict populations of Pleistocene apes and that, if their existence could be proved scientifically, they would lend support to his theory of the separate origins of human races.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] Coon's views on cryptids were a major influence on Grover Krantz, and the two were close friends in his later life.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] Coon's published magnum opus, *The Origin of Races* (1962), received mixed reactions from scientists of the era.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] Ernst Mayr praised the work for its synthesis as having an "invigorating freshness that will reinforce the current revitalization of physical anthropology".
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] A book review by Stanley Marion Garn criticised Coon's parallel view of the origin of the races with little gene flow but praised the work for its racial taxonomy and concluded: "an overall favorable report on the now famous Origin of Races".
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] Sherwood Washburn and Ashley Montagu were heavily influenced by the modern synthesis in biology and population genetics.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] In addition, they were influenced by Franz Boas, who had moved away from typological racial thinking.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] Rather than supporting Coon's theories, they and other contemporary researchers viewed the human species as a continuous serial progression of populations and heavily criticized Coon's *Origin of Races*.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] Howells, writing in a 1989 article, noted that Coon's research was "still regarded as a valuable source of data".
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] Goodman (2000) has said that Coon's main legacy was not his "separate evolution of races (Coon 1962)," but his "molding of race into the new physical anthropology of adaptive and evolutionary processes (Coon et al.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] They had two sons, one of whom, Carleton S.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] Coon Jr. went on to become Ambassador to Nepal.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] Coon and Goodale divorced and in 1945 he married Lisa Dougherty Geddes.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] He was a member of the Congregational Church.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] Coon retired from Pennsylvania in 1963, but retained an affiliation with the Peabody Museum and continued to write until the end of his life.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] He appeared on several episodes of television quiz show *What in the World?* between 1952 and 1957.
[src:eliot-chapple/carleton-stevens-coon] Coon died in Gloucester, Massachusetts on June 3, 1981.
[src:eliot-chapple/eliot-chapple] In 2000 he received the Conrad Arensberg Award (awarded for outstanding contributions to the field) from the American Anthropological Association.
[src:eliot-chapple/eliot-chapple] He received his Ph.D. from Harvard University in 1933.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Harvard was founded and authorized by the Massachusetts General Court, the governing legislature of colonial-era Massachusetts Bay Colony.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] While never formally affiliated with any Protestant denomination, Harvard trained Congregational clergy until its curriculum and student body were gradually secularized in the 18th century.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] In 1780, the Constitution of Massachusetts referred to it as a university, and a new medical school established in 1782 was named the Medical Institution of Harvard University; but this was a new name, not a new foundation.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Harvard College soon became the name of the university's undergraduate division.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] By the 19th century, Harvard had emerged as the most prominent academic and cultural institution among the Boston elite.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Following the American Civil War, under Harvard president Charles William Eliot's long tenure from 1869 to 1909, Harvard developed multiple professional schools, which transformed it into a modern research university.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] In 1900, Harvard co-founded the Association of American Universities.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Conant led the university through the Great Depression and World War II, and liberalized admissions after the war.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] The university has ten academic faculties and a faculty attached to Harvard Radcliffe Institute.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] The Faculty of Arts and Sciences offers study in a wide range of undergraduate and graduate academic disciplines, and other faculties offer graduate degrees, including professional degrees.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Harvard has three campuses: the main campus, a 209-acre (85 ha) in Cambridge centered on Harvard Yard; an adjoining campus immediately across Charles River in the Allston neighborhood of Boston; and the medical campus in Boston's Longwood Medical Area.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Harvard's endowment, valued at $55.7 billion, makes it the wealthiest academic institution in the world.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Harvard Library, with more than 20 million volumes, is the world's largest academic library.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Harvard students and alumni have also collectively won 10 Academy Awards and 110 Olympic medals, including 46 gold medals.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Harvard was founded in 1636 by a vote of the Great and General Court of the Massachusetts Bay Colony.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Its first headmaster, Nathaniel Eaton, took office the following year.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] In 1638, the university acquired English North America's first known printing press.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] The same year, on his deathbed, John Harvard, a Puritan clergyman who had emigrated to the colony from England, bequeathed the emerging college £780 and his library of some 320 volumes; the following year, it was named Harvard College.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] In its early years, the college trained many Puritan Congregational ministers and offered a classical curriculum based on the English university model exemplified by the University of Cambridge, where many colonial Massachusetts leaders had studied prior to emigrating to the colony.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Harvard College never formally affiliated with any particular Protestant denomination, but its curriculum conformed to the tenets of Puritanism.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] In 1650, the charter for Harvard Corporation, the college's governing body, was granted.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] From 1681 to 1701, Increase Mather, a Puritan clergyman, served as Harvard's sixth president.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] In 1708, John Leverett became Harvard's seventh president and the first president who was not also a clergyman.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] The earliest known official seal of Harvard College, commonly referred to as the Seal of 1650 or the In Christi Gloriam seal, features a square shield bearing three open books arranged around a central chevron.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] This design symbolizes the pursuit of learning under divine guidance.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] In 1885, the Harvard Corporation adopted a revised design known as the Appleton Seal, based on an earlier version created by President Josiah Quincy in 1843.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Designed by William Sumner Appleton (Harvard AB 1860), the seal features a triangular shield bearing three open books with the motto VERITAS ("Truth").
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Surrounding the shield is the motto CHRISTO ET ECCLESIÆ ("For Christ and the Church"), and the outer border bears the inscription SIGILLVM ACADEMIÆ HARVARDINÆ IN NOV.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] ("Seal of Harvard College in New England").
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] This version of the seal sought to harmonize the university's intellectual pursuits with its ecclesiastical roots.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Harvard faculty and students largely supported the Patriot cause during the American Revolution.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] In the second half of the 18th century, Harvard began granting graduate and doctorate-level degrees.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] In 1780, the Constitution of Massachusetts recognized Harvard College as a university, and when in 1783 a new medical school was established, it was given the formal name of the Medical Institution of Harvard University.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] This was a re-naming of the college, and not a re-founding.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] In the 19th century, Harvard was influenced by Enlightenment Age ideas, including reason and free will, which were widespread among Congregational ministers and which placed these ministers and their congregations at odds with more traditionalist, Calvinist pastors and clergies.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Following the death of Hollis Professor of Divinity David Tappan in 1803 and that of Joseph Willard, Harvard's eleventh president, the following year, a struggle broke out over their replacements.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] In 1805, Henry Ware was elected to replace Tappan as Hollis chair.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Two years later, in 1807, liberal Samuel Webber was appointed as Harvard's 13th president, representing a shift from traditional ideas at Harvard to more liberal and Arminian ideas.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] In 1816, Harvard University launched new language programs in the study of French and Spanish, and appointed George Ticknor the university's first professor for these language programs.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] From 1869 to 1909, Charles William Eliot, Harvard University's 21st president, decreased the historically favored position of Christianity in the curriculum, opening it to student self-direction.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Though Eliot was an influential figure in the secularization of U.S. higher education, he was motivated primarily by Transcendentalist and Unitarian convictions influenced by William Ellery Channing, Ralph Waldo Emerson, and others, rather than secularism.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] In the late 19th century, Harvard University's graduate schools began admitting women in small numbers.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] In 1900, Harvard became a founding member of the Association of American Universities.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] For the first few decades of the 20th century, the Harvard student body was predominantly "old-stock, high-status Protestants, especially Episcopalians, Congregationalists, and Presbyterians," according to sociologist and author Jerome Karabel.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Over the 20th century, as its endowment burgeoned and prominent intellectuals and professors affiliated with it, Harvard University's reputation as one of the world's most prestigious universities grew notably.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] The university's enrollment also underwent substantial growth, a product of both the founding of new graduate academic programs and an expansion of the undergraduate college.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Radcliffe College emerged as the female counterpart of Harvard College, becoming one of the most prominent schools in the nation for women.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] In 1923, a year after the proportion of Jewish students at Harvard reached 20%, A.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Lawrence Lowell, the university's 22nd president, unsuccessfully proposed capping the admission of Jewish students to 15% of the undergraduate population.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Between 1933 and 1953, Harvard University was led by James B.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Conant, the university's 23rd president, who reinvigorated the university's creative scholarship in an effort to guarantee Harvard's preeminence among the nation and world's emerging research institutions.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Conant viewed higher education as a vehicle of opportunity for the talented rather than an entitlement for the wealthy, and devised programs to identify, recruit, and support talented youth.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] In 1945, under Conant's leadership, an influential 268-page report, *General Education in a Free Society*, was published by Harvard faculty, which remains one of the most important works in curriculum studies, and women were first admitted to the medical school.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Between 1945 and 1960, admissions were standardized to open the university to a more diverse group of students.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Following the end of World War II, for example, special exams were developed so veterans could be considered for admission.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] No longer drawing mostly from prestigious prep schools in New England, the undergraduate college became accessible to striving middle class students from public schools; many more Jews and Catholics were admitted, but Blacks, Hispanics, and Asians remained underrepresented.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Over the second half of the 20th century, however, the university became incrementally more diverse.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Between 1971 and 1999, Harvard controlled undergraduate admission, instruction, and housing for Radcliffe's women; in 1999, Radcliffe was formally merged into Harvard University.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] On July 1, 2007, Drew Gilpin Faust, dean of Harvard Radcliffe Institute, was appointed Harvard's 28th and the university's first female president.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] On July 1, 2018, Faust retired and joined the board of Goldman Sachs, and Lawrence Bacow became Harvard's 29th president.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] In February 2023, approximately 6,000 Harvard workers attempted to organize a union.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Bacow retired in June 2023, and on July 1 Claudine Gay, a Harvard professor in the Government and African American Studies departments and dean of the Faculty of Arts and Sciences, became Harvard's 30th president.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] In January 2024, just six months into her presidency, Gay resigned following allegations of antisemitism and plagiarism.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Gay was succeeded by Alan Garber, the university's provost, who was appointed interim president.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] In August 2024, the university announced that Garber would be appointed Harvard's 31st president through the end of the 2026–27 academic year.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] In February 2025, Leo Terrell, the head of the Trump administration's Task Force to Combat Antisemitism, announced that he would investigate Harvard University as part of the Department of Justice's broader investigation into antisemitism on college campuses.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] In April 2025, the United States federal government under President Donald Trump threatened to withhold nearly $9 billion in government funds from the university unless the university complied with government demands to modify many of its policies.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] This threat was part of a broader battle over universities' autonomy following contentious student protests against the Gaza war, and followed similar demands made of Columbia University.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] The university's leadership resisted the government's demands, claiming that they were an unlawful overreach of government authority.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] In response, the US Department of Education announced they were freezing $2.3 billion in federal funds to Harvard.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] The Department of Homeland Security subsequently threatened to revoke Harvard's eligibility to host international students.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Harvard responded by filing a lawsuit against the Trump administration in the District Court of Massachusetts, arguing that the freezing of funds was unconstitutional.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] In May 2025, education secretary Linda McMahon informed Harvard president Garber that the federal government would no longer provide grant funding until the university complied with the Trump administration's demands.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] The following week, the Trump administration cut an additional $450 million in grants to the school.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Later that same month, Department of Homeland Security secretary Kristi Noem announced that Harvard's Student and Exchange Visitor Program certification had been revoked, barring Harvard from hosting international students.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] The following day, Harvard sued the Trump administration for banning them from enrolling international students and U.S.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] District Judge Allison Burroughs granted a temporary restraining order stopping the ban.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] On June 16, 2025, Burroughs postponed a ruling after hearing arguments from lawyers on both sides, leaving the temporary block in place for another week.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] On May 30, 2025, the State Department ordered all US embassies and consulates to conduct "comprehensive and thorough vetting" of the online presence of anyone seeking to visit Harvard from abroad.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] On June 4, 2025, Trump issued a proclamation restricting international students from studying at Harvard, and directing the State Department to consider revoking the visas of current international students studying at that university.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] The following day, Harvard filed a legal challenge, amending their existing federal complaint against the administration.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] On June 20, Harvard was granted an injunction allowing it to continue hosting international students as litigation continues.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] On June 30, a Trump administration investigation found Harvard violated federal civil rights law by failing to protect Jewish students, faculty, and staff.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] In February 2026, Trump announced that his administration would seek $1 billion in damages from Harvard.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] In a post on Truth Social, Trump accused Harvard of supplying misleading information to *The New York Times*.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Administration officials claimed that the university failed to adequately address antisemitism during pro-Palestinian protests, a claim Harvard has denied.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] On February 6, Secretary of Defense Pete Hegseth announced that the Pentagon would start to sever ties to Harvard with its graduate-level military training courses.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Hegseth accused Harvard of becoming a "factory for woke ideology and a breeding ground for anti-American radicals..." as a reason for discontinuing the programs.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] A week later, Harvard along with other prestigious American Universities was listed as “Moderate to High Risk” in a Department of Defense memo for Assisted Military Tuition, and could be barred for service members for tuition assistance.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] The 209-acre (85 ha) main campus of Harvard University is centered on Harvard Yard, colloquially known as "the Yard", in Cambridge, Massachusetts, about three miles (five km) west-northwest of downtown Boston, and extending to the surrounding Harvard Square neighborhood.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] The Yard houses several Harvard buildings, including four of the university's libraries, Houghton, Lamont, Pusey, and Widener.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Also on Harvard Yard are Massachusetts Hall, built between 1718 and 1720 and the university's oldest still standing building, Memorial Church, and University Hall.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Harvard Yard and adjacent areas include the main academic buildings of the Faculty of Arts and Sciences, including Sever Hall, Harvard Hall, and freshman dormitories.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Upperclassmen live in the twelve residential houses: nine south of Harvard Yard near the Charles River, and three on the Radcliffe Quadrangle, which formerly housed Radcliffe College students.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Each house is a community of undergraduates, faculty deans, and resident tutors, with its own dining hall, library, and recreational facilities.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Also on the main campus in Cambridge are the Law, Divinity (theology), Engineering and Applied Science, Design (architecture), Education, Kennedy (public policy), and Extension schools, and Harvard Radcliffe Institute in Radcliffe Yard.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Harvard also has commercial real estate holdings in Cambridge.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Harvard Business School, Harvard Innovation Labs, and many athletics facilities, including Harvard Stadium, are located on a 358-acre (145 ha) campus in the Allston section of Boston across the John W.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Weeks Bridge, which crosses the Charles River and connects the Allston and Cambridge campuses.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] The university is actively expanding into Allston, where it now owns more land than in Cambridge.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Plans include new construction and renovation for the Business School, a hotel and conference center, graduate student housing, Harvard Stadium, and other athletics facilities.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Paulson School of Engineering and Applied Sciences expanded into the new Allston-based Science and Engineering Complex (SEC), which is more than 500,000 square feet in size.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] SEC is adjacent to the Enterprise Research Campus, the Business School, and Harvard Innovation Labs, and designed to encourage technology- and life science-focused startups and collaborations with mature companies.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] The university's schools of Medicine, Dental Medicine, and Public Health are located on a 21-acre (8.5 ha) campus in the Longwood Medical and Academic Area in Boston, about 3.3 miles (5.3 km) south of the Cambridge campus.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Additional affiliates, including Massachusetts General Hospital, are located throughout Greater Boston.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Harvard owns Dumbarton Oaks, a research library in Washington, D.C., Harvard Forest in Petersham, Massachusetts, Concord Field Station in Estabrook Woods in Concord, Massachusetts, the Villa I Tatti research center in Florence, Italy, and the Center for Hellenic Studies in Greece.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] The Harvard Shanghai Center in Shanghai, China, and Arnold Arboretum in the Jamaica Plain neighborhood of Boston.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Harvard is governed by a combination of its Board of Overseers and the President and Fellows of Harvard College, which is also known as the Harvard Corporation.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] These two bodies, in turn, appoint the president of Harvard University.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] As of 2025, Harvard differs radically from its peer universities in two important ways.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] First, Harvard does not make its governing statutes publicly available, meaning that members of the Harvard community interested in reform must first persuade the university to give them a copy of those documents.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Second, Harvard does not have an academic senate like most of its peers, although it is currently attempting to create one.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Harvard has the largest university endowment in the world, valued at about $50.7 billion as of 2023.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] During the recession of 2007–2009, it suffered significant losses that forced large budget cuts, in particular temporarily halting construction on the Allston Science Complex.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] About $2 billion of investment income is annually distributed to fund operations.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Harvard's ability to fund its degree and financial aid programs depends on the performance of its endowment; a poor performance in fiscal year 2016 forced a 4.4% cut in the number of graduate students funded by the Faculty of Arts and Sciences.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Endowment income is critical, as only 22% of revenue is from students' tuition, fees, room, and board.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Since the 1970s, several student-led campaigns have advocated divesting Harvard's endowment from controversial holdings, including investments in South Africa during apartheid, Sudan during the Darfur genocide, and tobacco, fossil fuel, and private prison industries.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] In the late 1980s, during the disinvestment from South Africa movement, student activists erected a symbolic shanty town on Harvard Yard and blockaded a speech by South African Vice Consul Duke Kent-Brown.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] In response to pressure, the university eventually reduced its South African holdings by $230 million out of a total of $400 million between 1986 and 1987.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Harvard is a large, highly residential research university offering 50 undergraduate majors, 134 graduate degrees, and 32 professional degrees.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] During the 2018–2019 academic year, Harvard granted 1,665 baccalaureate degrees, 1,013 graduate degrees, and 5,695 professional degrees.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] The Faculty of Arts and Sciences, with an academic staff of 1,211 as of 2019, is the largest Harvard faculty, and has primary responsibility for instruction in Harvard College, the Graduate School of Arts and Sciences, the John A.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Paulson School of Engineering and Applied Sciences (SEAS), and the Division of Continuing Education, which includes Harvard Summer School and Harvard Extension School.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] There are nine other graduate and professional faculties and a faculty attached to the Harvard Radcliffe Institute.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] There are four Harvard joint programs with MIT, which include the Harvard–MIT Program in Health Sciences and Technology, the Broad Institute, The Observatory of Economic Complexity, and edX.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Harvard College, the four-year, full-time undergraduate program, has a liberal arts and sciences focus.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] To graduate in the usual four years, undergraduates normally take 16 credit hours (usually across four courses) per semester for a total of 128 credit hours.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] In most majors, an honors degree requires advanced coursework and a senior thesis.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Though some introductory courses have large enrollments, the median class size is 12 students.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Harvard Medical School, the third-oldest medical school in the United States, was founded in 1782 as Massachusetts Medical College by John Warren, Benjamin Waterhouse, and Aaron Dexter.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] In 1810, Harvard Medical School relocated from Cambridge to Boston.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] The medical school was tied to the rest of the university "only by the tenuous thread of degrees", but its strong faculty gave it a national reputation by the early 19th century.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] The medical school moved to its current location on Longwood Avenue in 1906, where the "Great White Quadrangle" or HMS Quad with its five white marble buildings was established.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Harvard Medical School's reputation continued to grow into the 20th century, especially in terms of scientific research and support from regional and national elites.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Fifteen scientists won the Nobel Prize for work done at the Medical School.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Its four major flagship teaching hospitals are Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center, Brigham and Women's Hospital, Boston Children's Hospital and Massachusetts General Hospital.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] The establishment of Harvard Law School in 1817 was made possible by a 1779 bequest from Isaac Royall Jr.; it is the oldest continuously operating law school in the nation.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] It was a small operation and grew slowly.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] By 1827, it was down to one faculty member.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Nathan Dane, a prominent alumnus, endowed the Dane Professorship of Law and insisted that it be given to then Supreme Court Justice Joseph Story.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] For a while, the school was called Dane Law School.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Story's belief in the need for an elite law school based on merit and dedicated to public service helped build the school's reputation at the time.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Enrollment remained low as academic legal education was considered to be of little added benefit to apprenticeships in legal practice.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Radical reform came in the 1870s, under Dean Christopher Columbus Langdell (1826–1906).
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Its new curriculum set the national standard and was copied widely in the United States.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Langdell developed the case method of teaching law, based on his belief that law could be studied as a "science" gave university legal education a reason for being distinct from vocational preparation.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] The school introduced a first-year curriculum that was widely imitated, based on classes in contracts, property, torts, criminal law and civil procedure.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Critics bemoaned abandonment of the more traditional lecture method, because of its efficiency and the lower workloads it placed on faculty and students.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Advocates of the case method had a sounder theoretical basis in scientific research and the inductive method.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Langdell's graduates became leading professors at other law schools where they introduced the case method.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] From its founding in 1900, the Association of American Law Schools promoted the case method in law schools that sought accreditation.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] As the college modernized in the late 19th century, the faculty was organized into departments and began to add graduate programs, including the PhD.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Charles William Eliot, president from 1869 to 1909, was a chemist who had spent two years in Germany studying at their universities.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Thousands of Americans, mostly Harvard and Yale alumni, had attended German universities, especially Berlin and Göttingen.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Eliot used the German model to set up graduate programs at Harvard and he formed a graduate department in 1872, which granted its first Ph.D. degrees in 1873 to William Byerly in mathematics and Charles Whitney in history.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Eliot set up the Graduate School of Arts and Sciences with its own dean and budget in 1890, which dealt with graduate students and funded research programs.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] By 2004, there were 3,200 graduate students in 53 separate programs and forty former or current professors had won a Nobel Prize, most of them scientists or economists based in the Graduate School of Arts and Sciences.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] From its founding in 1908, Harvard Business School has had a close relationship with the corporate world.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Within a few years of its founding, many business leaders were its alumni and were hiring other alumni for starting positions in their firms.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] The school used Rockefeller funding in the 1920s to launch a major research program under Elton Mayo (1926–1947) for his "Harvard human relations group".
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Its findings revolutionized human relations in business and raised the reputation of the Business School from its initial "low status as a trainer of money grabbers into a high prestige educator of socially-conscientious administrators".
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Starting in 1935, the school began weekend and short-term leadership training workshops for executives of major corporations that further expanded its national role.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] By 1949, nearly half of all the holders of the MBA degree in the U.S. were alumni of Harvard Business School, and it was considered "the most influential graduate school of business".
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Chan School of Public Health is the public health school of Harvard University, located in the Longwood Medical Area of Boston.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] The school grew out of the Harvard-MIT School for Health Officers, the nation's first graduate training program in population health, which was founded in 1913 and then became the Harvard School of Public Health in 1922.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] The school was part of Harvard Medical School until 1946, when it became a fully autonomous institution with its own dedicated public health and medical faculty.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Chan School of Public Health in 2014 in honor of a $350 million donation from the Morningside Foundation.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] In 1936, Harvard University founded the Harvard Graduate School of Public Administration, later renamed Harvard Kennedy School in honor of former U.S.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] President and 1940 Harvard College alumnus John F.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] The Kennedy School has an endowment of $1.7 billion as of 2021 and is routinely ranked at the top of the world's graduate schools in public policy, social policy, international affairs, and government.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Its alumni include 17 heads of state or government.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Harvard is a founding member of the Association of American Universities and a preeminent research university with "very high" research activity (R1) and comprehensive doctoral programs across the arts, sciences, engineering, and medicine, according to the Carnegie Classification.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] The medical school consistently ranks first among medical schools for research, and biomedical research is an area of particular strength for the university.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] More than 11,000 faculty and 1,600 graduate students conduct research at the medical school and its 15 affiliated hospitals and research institutes.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] In 2019, the medical school and its affiliates attracted $1.65 billion in competitive research grants from the National Institutes of Health, more than twice that of any other university.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Harvard Library, the largest academic library in the world with 20.4 million holdings, is centered in Widener Library in Harvard Yard.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] It includes 25 individual Harvard libraries around the world with a combined staff of more than 800 librarians and personnel.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Houghton Library, the Arthur and Elizabeth Schlesinger Library on the History of Women in America, and the Harvard University Archives consist principally of rare and unique materials.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] The nation's oldest collection of maps, gazetteers, and atlases is stored in Pusey Library on Harvard Yard, which is open to the public.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] The largest collection of East-Asian language material outside of East Asia is held in Harvard-Yenching Library.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Harvard Art Museums include three museums: the Arthur M.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Harvard Museums of Science and Culture include the Harvard Museum of Natural History, which itself includes the Harvard Mineralogical and Geological Museum, the Harvard University Herbaria featuring the Blaschka Glass Flowers exhibit, and the Museum of Comparative Zoology.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Harvard University is accredited by the New England Commission of Higher Education.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Since its founding in 2003, the *Academic Ranking of World Universities* has ranked Harvard first in each of its annual rankings of the world's colleges and universities.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Similarly, the *Times Higher Education–QS World University Rankings*, which was published from 2004 to 2009, ranked Harvard first in the world in each of its annual rankings.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Since then, Harvard has been ranked first in the world each year since 2011 by its successor, the *Times Higher Education World University Rankings*.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Harvard was also ranked in the first tier of American research universities, along with Columbia, MIT, and Stanford, in the 2023 report from the Center for Measuring University Performance.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Among rankings of specific indicators, Harvard topped both the University Ranking by Academic Performance in 2019–20 and *Mines ParisTech: Professional Ranking of World Universities* in 2011, which measured universities' numbers of alumni holding CEO positions in *Fortune* Global 500 companies.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] According to annual polls done by The Princeton Review, Harvard is consistently among the top two most commonly named dream colleges in the United States for both students and their parents.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] In 2019, Harvard's engineering school was ranked the third-best school in the world for engineering and technology by *Times Higher Education*.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] In international relations, *Foreign Policy* magazine ranks Harvard best in the world at the undergraduate level and second in the world at the graduate level, behind the Walsh School of Foreign Service at Georgetown University.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] The Undergraduate Council represented Harvard College undergraduate students until it was dissolved in 2022 and replaced by the Undergraduate Association.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] The Graduate Council represents students at all twelve graduate and professional schools, most of which also have their own student government.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Harvard College competes in the NCAA Division I Ivy League conference.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] The school fields 42 intercollegiate sports teams, more than any other college in the country.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Harvard and the other seven Ivy League universities are prohibited from offering athletic scholarships.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] The fencing team won the 2006 NCAA team championship in men's and women's combined fencing.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Representing Harvard Crimson, Benjamin (Benji) Ungar won Gold in the 2006 Individual Men's Épée event at the NCAA Fencing Championship, and was named Harvard Athlete of The Year.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] In 2020, the fencing program received more attention following a student admission scandal which involved former fencing coach Peter Brand accepting bribes to admit at least two sons of Maryland businessman Jie “Jack” Zhao into Harvard as members of the fencing team.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] The men's ice hockey team is one of the oldest intercollegiate ice hockey teams in the United States, having played their first game on January 19, 1898, in a 0–6 loss to Brown.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Claflin and former captain George Owen are credited with the first use of line change in a game against Yale on March 3, 1923, when the Crimson substituted entire forward lines instead of individuals.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] The men's ice hockey team won the NCAA Division I Championship on April 1, 1989, defeating the Minnesota Golden Gophers 4–3 in overtime.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] The Cleary Cup, awarded to the ECAC regular-season champion, is named for former Harvard All-American hockey player, coach, and athletic director Bill Cleary, a member of the U.S. hockey team that won the 1960 Winter Olympics gold medal.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] The team competes in ECAC Hockey along with five other Ivy League schools and is coached by Harvard alumnus, Olympian, and former NHL forward, Ted Donato.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Harvard competes in one of the most heated rivalries of college hockey at least twice each season against Harvard's archrival, the Cornell Big Red, in installments of the Cornell–Harvard hockey rivalry.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Cornell and Harvard are the most storied programs currently in the ECAC.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] In the NCAA Division I era, which began in 1973, Harvard Crimson teams have won five NCAA Division I championships as of 2024: men's ice hockey in 1989, women's lacrosse in 1990, women's rowing in 2003, and men's fencing in 2006 and 2024.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Including the pre-NCAA era, Harvard has won 159 national championships across all sports.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Its men's squash team holds the record for the most national collegiate championships in the sport.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Harvard's first national championship came in 1880, when its track and field team won the national championship.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Harvard's athletic programs maintain a long-standing rivalry with Yale in all sports, especially in college football, where Harvard and Yale compete in an annual football rivalry, which has played 139 times as of 2024, dating back to its first meeting in 1875.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Every two years, Harvard and Yale track and field teams come together to compete against a combined Oxford and Cambridge team in the oldest continuous international amateur competition in the world.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] In men's ice hockey, Harvard maintains a historic rivalry with Cornell, which dates back to their first meeting in 1910.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] In men's rugby, Harvard maintains a rivalry with McGill, as demonstrated by the biennial Harvard-McGill rugby games, alternately played in Montreal and Cambridge.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] A 2024 study analyzed the educational backgrounds of the most successful and influential Americans—"30 different achievement groups totaling 26,198 people"—and found that Harvard alumni were unusually dominant.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] A 2025 study of 6,141 of the most influential people in the world discovered that Harvard alumni are massively overrepresented among the global elite, and that this finding remains true when all American elites are removed.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Among the world's universities and colleges, Harvard has the most U.S. presidents (eight), living billionaires (188), Nobel laureates (162), Pulitzer Prize winners (48), Fields Medal recipients (seven), Marshall scholars (252), and Rhodes Scholars (369) among its alumni.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Harvard alumni also include nine Turing Award laureates, ten Academy Awards winners, and 108 Olympic medalists, including 46 gold medal winners.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] Harvard's reputation as a center of elite achievement or elitist privilege has made it a frequent literary and cinematic backdrop.
[src:eliot-chapple/harvard-university] "In the grammar of film, Harvard has come to mean both tradition, and a certain amount of stuffiness," film critic Paul Sherman said in 2010.
[src:eliot-chapple/project-muse] Project MUSE was founded in 1993 as a joint project between the Johns Hopkins University Press and the Milton S.
[src:eliot-chapple/project-muse] Eisenhower Library at the Johns Hopkins University.
[src:eliot-chapple/project-muse] Mellon Foundation and the National Endowment for the Humanities, Project MUSE was launched online alongside the JHU Press Journals in 1995.
[src:eliot-chapple/project-muse] In January 2012, MUSE launched its eBook Collections on the platform in collaboration with the University Press Content Consortium (UPCC), fully integrating them for search and discovery alongside its established journal collections.
[src:eliot-chapple/project-muse] Project MUSE announced in 2023 the launch of its Subscribe to Open (S2O) program, an open access initiative launched in 2025.
[src:eliot-chapple/project-muse] This program allows participating journals to make their content freely available to all readers if a minimum subscription revenue threshold is met during the year.
[src:eliot-chapple/project-muse] In 2024, Project MUSE said it will continue to serve libraries worldwide with access to a wide range of humanities and social science research materials, including thousands of open access books and several open access journals.
[src:eliot-chapple/project-muse] Project MUSE offers tiered-pricing structures to meet budgetary and research needs of subscribing institutions.
[src:eliot-chapple/project-muse] Project Muse is also the sole source of full-text versions of journal titles from a number of university presses and scholarly societies.
[src:eliot-chapple/project-muse] Supported by two grants from the Andrew W.
[src:eliot-chapple/project-muse] Mellon Foundation, The University Press e-book Consortium (UPeC) emerged in 2009 to explore the feasibility of, and later develop, a university press-based e-book initiative that would balance the interests of both the publishing and library communities.
[src:eliot-chapple/project-muse] In Spring 2011, UPeC announced its partnership with Project MUSE, and the University Press Content Consortium (UPCC) Book Collections on Project Muse was established.
[src:eliot-chapple/project-muse] Launched in January 2012, the UPCC Book Collections consist of thousands of peer-reviewed book titles from major university presses and related scholarly publishers.
[src:eliot-chapple/project-muse] Book collections are fully integrated with MUSE's electronic journal collections, allowing users to search across books and journals simultaneously or limit searches by content type.
[src:eliot-chapple/project-muse] In 2016, it launched an initiative to create an open access platform that also digitized out-of-print scholarly books under the effort called MUSE Open.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] The Sarasota area was explored by the Spanish in the 16th century, and was settled by American William Henry Whitaker in the mid-19th century.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Sarasota's development accelerated in the late 19th and early 20th centuries, particularly with the influence of Bertha Honore Palmer and the Ringling family as the home of Ringling Bros. and Barnum & Bailey Circus.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] The city's economy is based on tourism, healthcare, education, and real estate.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Its cultural attractions include the John and Mable Ringling Museum of Art, Sarasota Opera, and numerous galleries and theaters.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Sarasota city limits contain several barrier islands between Sarasota Bay and the Gulf of Mexico, including Lido Key, St.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Armands Key, Bird Key, and the northern portion of Siesta Key.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Its coastline, including nearby Siesta Beach, draws visitors year-round.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] The origin of the name is disputed and has given rise to several theories.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Two theories involve Hernando de Soto's visit to the area in 1539.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] One holds that he named it after his daughter, Sara; however, he had no children.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Chapline created this story in 1906, including an ill-fated romance between Sara and a Seminole prince, Chichi Okobee.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Another holds that it was named "Zara Soto", Arabic for the "Radiance of Soto".
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Other theories take into account the substantial beaches and indigenous mounds, with early Spanish explorers being reminded of the Sahara, combined with "zota", the indigenous word for "blue waters".
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Others claim that it comes from "sara-de-cota", meaning "an area of land easily observed" in the language of the Calusa indigenous tribe.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] The area known today as Sarasota appeared on a sheepskin Spanish map from 1763 with the word *Zarazote* over present-day Sarasota and Bradenton.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] In 1776, a British map by Bernard Romans lists a "Boca Sarasota" in the local area.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Maps in the 1700s showed the area as "Sarazota" or "Porte Sarasote".
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] A fishing camp and trading post on Longboat Key was also called "Saraxota".
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] The name Sarasota appears on the first maps of the state of Florida in 1839, after having passed into the ownership of the United States.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] People from Sarasota are generally known as "Sarasotans".
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Around 1883 to 1885, The Florida Mortgage and Investment Company of Edinburgh bought 60,000 acres (240 km2) for development in what is now Sarasota.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Many Scottish people began to arrive in Sarasota in December 1885.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] The municipal government of Sarasota was established when it was incorporated as a town on October 14, 1902.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] John Hamilton Gillespie was the first Mayor of the town government.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] When reincorporated with a city form of government on May 13, 1913, A.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Edwards became the first mayor of the city government.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] The city limits expanded significantly with the real estate rush of the early twentieth century, reaching almost 70 square miles (180 km2).
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] The speculation boom began to crash in 1926 and the city limits began to contract, shrinking to less than a quarter of that area.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Sarasota has a humid subtropical climate (Koppen *Cfa*) with hot, humid summers and cooler, milder winters.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] The high temperatures and high humidity in the summer regularly push the heat index over 100 °F (38 °C).
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] There are distinct rainy and dry seasons, with the rainy season lasting from March to November and the dry season from December to February.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Census Bureau, the city has a total area of 24.08 square miles (62.4 km2), of which 14.70 sq mi (38.07 km2) is land and 9.39 sq mi (24.3 km2) is water.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] The Gulf Intracoastal Waterway is the name given to the many natural deep water sections as well as humanmade channels, canals, and cuts that link the entire Sarasota Bay system.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] As of the 2020 census, Sarasota had a population of 54,842.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] About 3.9% of residents were under age 5, 14.2% of residents were under the age of 18 and 29.5% of residents were 65 years of age or older.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Females comprised 52.5% of the population.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] For every 100 females there were 91.4 males, and for every 100 females age 18 and over there were 89.2 males age 18 and over.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] 99.8% of residents lived in urban areas, while 0.2% lived in rural areas.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] There were 25,147 households in Sarasota, of which 17.8% had children under the age of 18 living in them.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Of all households, 35.0% were married-couple households, 21.8% were households with a male householder and no spouse or partner present, and 35.4% were households with a female householder and no spouse or partner present.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] About 39.8% of all households were made up of individuals and 20.5% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] There were 31,366 housing units, of which 19.8% were vacant.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] The homeowner vacancy rate was 3.2% and the rental vacancy rate was 11.0%.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] The 2016–2020 American Community Survey estimated 12,474 families in the city.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] The survey counted 4,056 veterans and reported that 16.7% of residents were foreign born.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] The median gross rent was $1,177; 92.5% of households had a computer and 84.2% had a broadband internet subscription.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] About 90.0% of residents ages 25 and older had completed high school, and 37.2% held a bachelor's degree or higher.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] The median household income was $56,093 and the per capita income was $43,387, with 15.6% of residents living below the poverty threshold.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] As of the 2010 United States census, there were 51,917 people, 22,775 households, and 11,603 families residing in the city.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Sarasota is home to Mote Marine Laboratory, a marine rescue, research facility, an aquarium, the Marie Selby Botanical Gardens, the Sarasota Jungle Gardens and the Big Cat Habitat & Gulf Coast Sanctuary.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] One of Sarasota's nicknames is "Circus City", or alternatively "The Circus Capital of the World", owing in part to John Ringling's decision to move the winter quarters of Ringling Bros. and Barnum & Bailey Circus to Sarasota in 1927.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] The John and Mable Ringling Museum of Art houses the Circus Museum and the Tibbals Learning Center, established in 1948.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Sarasota is also home to The Circus Arts Conservatory, which is responsible for the tent show Circus Sarasota and the "oldest youth circus", Sailor Circus.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] In 2017, The Circus Arts Conservatory took part in the Smithsonian Folk Festival.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] The Showfolks Club, a social organization that also puts on an annual circus performance billed as "Sarasota's longest running circus event", is located in Sarasota.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] The Circus Ring of Fame is a series of commemorative plaques in St.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Armand's Circle, honoring prominent figures in circus history, similar to the Hollywood Walk of Fame.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Honorees include Paul Binder, Nik Wallenda, and the King Charles Troupe, among over 150 others.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Residents of Sarasota that have been associated with the circus include daredevil and Guinness World Record holder Bello Nock, himself an honoree of the Circus Ring of Fame, as well as aerialist and circus proprietor Dolly Jacobs, who cofounded The Circus Arts Conservatory.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Since 1998, the city has hosted the Sarasota Film Festival annually.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] The festival attracts independent films from around the world.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] It claims to be one of Florida's largest film festivals.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] In 2009 the annual Ringling International Arts Festival, held its premier and held its closing event in the historic Asolo theater, which had been moved and rebuilt again.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] The historic Venetian theater now is housed in the reception building for the museum where it is used for special events as well as performances, informative purposes, and another seasonal film series hosted by the museum.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Florida Studio Theatre produces the annual Sarasota Improv Festival.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Founded in 2009 by Rebecca Hopkins, FST's annual Sarasota Improv Festival brings together improvisers from across the country and worldwide.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] The Festival has become a destination event, drawing thousands across Florida and beyond.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Past performers have come from as far as Mexico, Canada, Spain, France, and the United Kingdom to perform on Florida's Gulf Coast.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] In 2010, the Sarasota Chalk Festival that is held yearly in the historic area of Burns Square became the first international street painting festival in the United States.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Celebrating the sixteenth-century performance art of Italian street painting, the festival hosted Maestro Madonnaro Edgar Mueller from Germany, who created the first street painting that changed images from day to night.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] The festival has a different theme each year and has introduced new techniques in street art.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Other applications of street art such as murals and "cellograff graffiti" have become companion events also produced by Avenida de Colores, Inc.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] The murals are part of the "Going Vertical" project, and although it sometimes coincides with the chalk festival, it is distinct from it and often continues throughout the year.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Except for a few commissioned on public property in the Palm Avenue Parking Garage, the murals are on private property and are in many sections of Sarasota and Manatee County.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] As of 2014 the Sarasota Chalk festival has relocated to Venice, south of Sarasota.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] The name Sarasota Chalk Festival remains the same.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] It is also home to the Fabulous Arts Foundation, formerly the Harvey Milk Festival, an independent music festival in support of civil rights, focusing on the LGBTQ community.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] It has been celebrated in May annually since 2010 on the weekend closest to Harvey Milk's birthday.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] It is currently the largest independent music festival in Sarasota, with thousands of attendees throughout the free, public, multi-day event that also includes gallery showings, film, and other live performances.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Sarasota is home to the Whiskey Obsession Festival, the largest whiskey festival in Florida.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Established in 2013, the festival features several hundred whiskies from around the world.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Dozens of professional brand ambassadors and distillers participate in the festival by engaging in panel discussions, leading classes, and tastings.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Sarasota is the home of the Sarasota Orchestra, which was founded by Ruth Cotton Butler in 1949 and known for years as the *Florida West Coast Symphony*.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] It holds a three-week *Sarasota Music Festival* that is recognized internationally and boasts it attracts renowned teachers and the finest students of chamber music.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Sarasota also boasts a symphonic chorus, Key Chorale, and professional vocal ensemble, Choral Artists of Sarasota.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] The Jazz Club of Sarasota is one of the largest and most active jazz clubs in the United States and has promoted jazz events in Sarasota for 39 years.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Joe Perry of Aerosmith, Brian Johnson of AC/DC, Dickey Betts of the Allman Brothers Band, Donald Dunn of the Blues Brothers and Graeme Edge of the Moody Blues have all settled in Sarasota.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Sarasota is home to a vibrant performing arts scene, with numerous venues dedicated to music, dance, theatre, circus arts, and more.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Among its many institutions are the Sarasota Ballet, Sarasota Opera, Asolo Repertory Theatre, Van Wezel Performing Arts Hall, and Florida Studio Theatre.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] These venues, along with others like the Players Centre for Performing Arts and Sarasota Contemporary Dance, contribute to a culturally rich and diverse arts community.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Several of Sarasota's theaters have historical significance.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] The Sarasota Opera House began as the Edward Theatre in 1925, hosting stars like Elvis Presley and Will Rogers before becoming a permanent home for the Sarasota Opera.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] The Historic Asolo Theater, imported from Asolo, Italy, and reconstructed by the Ringling Museum in the 1950s, originally served Queen Catherine Cornaro of Cyprus.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] In the 1980s, another Asolo Theater, part of the Florida State University Center for the Performing Arts, was constructed around the historic Dunfermline Opera House from Scotland, housing the FSU/Asolo Conservatory for Actor Training and hosting film festivals and theatrical performances.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Florida Studio Theatre (FST) has preserved and repurposed several historic buildings.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Its Keating Theatre, once the Sarasota Woman's Club founded in 1903, served as the town's first library and community hub before being saved from demolition in 1976.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] The building was added to the National Register of Historic Places in 1985 and later expanded.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] FST also acquired the Gompertz Theatre, originally a 1920s movie house that underwent various transformations before becoming part of FST in 2003.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Sarasota and the Cultural Coast are home to fine art, film-making, circus history and performance, and decorative arts.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] The Sarasota Art Museum and the John and Mable Ringling Museum of Art are both in Sarasota.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] A large number of homes and buildings are designed in the Italian style.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Italian architecture and culture are present in the area including at the John and Mable Ringling Museum of Art.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Ringling's home, Cà d'Zan, was mostly modeled on the Venetian.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Examples of those more typically seen in the same style are the residences of Edith Ringling and of Hester Ringling Lancaster Sanford, that also are among the structures in the Caples–Ringling Estates Historic District.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Italian inspired statues are also common and the copy of Michelangelo's David at the museum is used as the symbol of Sarasota.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] The Sarasota School of Architecture developed as a variant of mid-century modernist architecture.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] It incorporates elements of both the Bauhaus and Frank Lloyd Wright's "organic" architecture.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] The style developed as an adaptation to the area's sub-tropical climate and used newly emerging materials that were manufactured or implemented following World War II.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] By the end of the twentieth century, many of Sarasota's more modest historical structures were demolished.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Recently, two historic buildings, the Crocker Church and the Bidwell-Wood House (the oldest remaining structure in the city), first restored by Veronica Morgan and members of the Sarasota Alliance for Historic Preservation that she founded, became city property.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] These structures were relocated to this park, despite protests from residents who objected to the loss of park area.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] In the late 1970s, Sarasota County purchased the Terrace Hotel that Charles Ringling built and renovated it for use as a county government office building.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] The adjacent courthouse that he donated to the new county in 1921 has been listed on the National Register of Historic Places.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] The courthouse complex was designed by Dwight James Baum.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] In the next decade, the landmark hotel built by Owen Burns, the El Vernona, which had been turned into apartments, became endangered.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] By then, it was called the John Ringling Towers and was purchased by a phosphate miner, Gardinier, who wanted to turn it into his corporate headquarters.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Plans were made to restore the building.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] The city commissioners initially supported the plan, but lobbying to undermine the project began, and one of the commissioners changed her vote.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] The project was denied at the final hearing.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Remarkable preservation success occurred during the 1990s when the community exhibition hall, the Municipal Auditorium, designed by Thomas Reed Martin and Clarence A.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Martin, was listed on the National Register of Historic Places and meticulously restored to its depression recovery era, 1937 WPA community project, completion status, and its architectural glory—both inside and out.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Later the Federal Building, designed by George Albee Freeman (the designer of Seagate for industrialist Powell Crosley Jr.) and Louis A.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Simon, which initially had served as the post office was restored as well.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Most of the luxurious historic residences from the 1920s boom period along the northern shore of Sarasota Bay also have survived.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] This string of homes, built on large parcels of elevated land along the widest point of the bay, is anchored by the John and Mable Ringling Museum of Art at its center.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Many significant structures from the comparatively recent "Sarasota School of Architecture" period of the mid-twentieth century, however, have not survived.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Since they do not qualify under the age criteria set for historic preservation nominations, their historical aspect often escapes public recognition.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Others frequently are threatened by demolition plans for new development without consideration of their cultural and historical importance to the community instead of motivating the implementation of plans to retain the buildings and integrate them into new plans.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] In 2006, the Sarasota County School Board slated one of Paul Rudolph's largest Sarasota projects, Riverview High School, for demolition.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] The board decided despite protests by many community members, including architects, historic preservationists, and urban planners.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Others supported the demolition as they believed the structure was no longer functional.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] The World Monuments Fund included the school on its *2008 Watch List of 100 Most Endangered Sites* in the category *Main Street Modern*.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Following a March 2007 charrette led by the National Trust for Historic Preservation, a proposal was advanced to renovate and preserve Rudolph's buildings.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] The school board decided to allow a year to consider implementing the innovative plan proposed to preserve the buildings, which would include building a parking garage with playing fields above it rather than demolishing the structures.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] In early June 2008, the school board voted in a 3–2 decision to allow the demolition; School board members Shirley Brown, Caroline Zucker and Frank Kovatch voted against preserving the historic high school.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] This decision was that school would be demolished and that a parking lot would replace it.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] One year later, in June 2009, Riverview High School was demolished.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] In December 2019, a former Sarasota High School facility was transformed into the Sarasota Art Museum of Ringling College.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] The 93-year-old building was renovated to include 80,000 square feet for the museum's campus with about 15,000 square feet for exhibitions, costing about $30 million according to the president of Ringling College, Larry Thompson.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] *Breaking Amish: Brave New World*, a television series of scripted reality is set in Pinecraft.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] The Rosemary District was an African American community and is home to the Boulevard of the Arts.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Newtown is predominantly and historically African American.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Sarasota is home to the Sarasota Paradise, a Professional team that plays in the USL League One, founded in 2023, the team plays its games at Premier Sports Campus.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] In 2013, Sarasota became the home of the Sarasota Thunder, which was to play in the Ultimate Indoor Football League, but the team folded.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Sarasota and Bradenton together held the 2021 U-18 Baseball World Cup.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] In 2010, declining sponsorship and marathon registration led organizers to change the event to a half marathon.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] The race begins and ends near the John and Mable Ringling Museum.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] In 2014, Sarasota hosted the modern pentathlon World Cup Final.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] The Sarasota Sharks have won national championships.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] A newer team, the Sarasota Tsunami, was founded by the former Sharks head coach and is also nationally competitive.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] The Sarasota Sailing Squadron is a highly active facility that has hosted many nationally renowned regattas for both dinghies and larger vessels.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] In 1937 the Municipal Auditorium-Recreation Club was built with funds provided by the Works Progress Administration, the municipal government, and local residents and business owners.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] It became a center for sports, entertainment, and recreation.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] The sports activities have ranged from badminton, basketball, boating, lawn bowling, and shuffleboard, to tennis.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] The auditorium hosts clubs for cards, dancing, games, gardening, and numerous hobbies as well as having become the community meeting place for commercial and educational shows and the venue for local schools and charities to hold events and dances.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Tourists are attracted to exhibitions provided by local businesses as well as vendors from national circuits.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] This building was listed in the National Register of Historic Places because of its architecture and for providing the enormous range of community activities that are scheduled at it every week.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Sarasota is home to Ed Smith Stadium where the Baltimore Orioles have held spring training since 2010.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] The Orioles also have minor league facilities at the Buck O'Neil Baseball Complex at Twin Lakes Park.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Previously, Ed Smith Stadium was the spring training home of the Cincinnati Reds and the minor league Sarasota Reds.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] The warm climate helped the Sarasota area become a popular golf destination.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] John Hamilton Gillespie was an early pioneer of the game in Sarasota.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] The Sara Bay course in the Whitfield area was designed by golf architect Donald Ross.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Bobby Jones was associated with the community course in Sarasota.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Many courses dot the area, including the one originally laid out for the hotel John Ringling planned on the southern tip of Longboat Key.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Sport fishing attracts enthusiasts to Sarasota as a result of the action that the bay offers.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Tarpon was the biggest draw, but gigantic gar as well as many other species abounded to attract the notable Owen Burns and Powel Crosley.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Nathan Benderson Park contains a lake with a specialized 2,000 meter eight-lane rowing course.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] It was the venue for the World Rowing Championships in 2017, held on September 23 – October 1, 2017.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] The park has been the site of USRowing's Youth National Championship Regatta in June 2015, 2017, 2021, 2022 and 2023 and has hosted the NCAA women's rowing national championship (Division I, Division II and Division III) in 2018, 2021 and 2022.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] The park has also hosted trials of the men's and women's U.S. teams for the Summer Olympic Games of 2016 and 2020.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Sarasota was reincorporated as a city on May 13, 1913.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Thereafter, it was called the "City of Sarasota".
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Sarasota later was designated as the county seat when Sarasota County was carved out of Manatee County in 1921 during the creation of several new counties.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] In 1945 the commission-manager government form was adopted for the city and it is governed by a five-person commission elected by popular vote, two members of which serve in the ceremonial positions of "mayor" and "vice-mayor", as chosen by the commission every April.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Two at-large commissioners are elected by all voters, and the city is divided into three districts for which the residents of each elect one district representative to the five-member commission.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Debbie Trice was voted Mayor for 202–2026 period.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Sarasota has an official seal, which was adopted in 2022, replacing the original seal that was adopted in 1902.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Sarasota's seal also has the city motto on it: "May Sarasota Prosper".
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] The city seal consists of a silhouette of the Statue of David.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Sarasota was then reincorporated as a city on May 13, 1913.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Since its incorporation, Sarasota has been governed by a commission–manager form of government.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] There are a total of five city commissioners: two that are elected "at large" and three from single-member districts.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] The mayor and vice mayor are selected from the five city commissioners.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Public primary and secondary education is provided by the Sarasota County Public Schools school district.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] The district includes 15 elementary schools, five middle schools, and the following secondary schools: Booker High School, Pine View School for the Gifted, Riverview High School, Sarasota High School, Suncoast Polytechnical High School, Sarasota Military Academy, and Oak Park School.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Sarasota was also home to the Flint School, a preparatory school for boating.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Private education includes Liberty Christian Academy, Ascension Lutheran School, The Classical Academy of Sarasota, Sarasota Christian School, Cardinal Mooney Catholic High School and Out-of-Door Academy.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] In higher education, Sarasota is home to New College of Florida, a public liberal arts college and the honors college for the State University System of Florida.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Petersburg, Florida; and Florida State University College of Medicine, based in Tallahassee, Florida.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Other colleges in the city include East West College of Natural Medicine, an accredited college of acupuncture and Chinese medicine.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Nearby educational institutions with regional draw include State College of Florida, Manatee-Sarasota, and a commuter branch of the University of South Florida, with the main campus located in Tampa.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Sarasota is part of the Nielsen-designated Tampa-Saint Petersburg-Sarasota television market.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] The local television stations are ABC-affiliate WWSB and the SNN: Suncoast News Network, a continuous local cable news operation run by Comcast, Frontier FiOS and the *Sarasota Herald-Tribune*.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] WWSB is the only network station with studios in Sarasota.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Other network and public television programming serving the community is offered by Fort Myers and Tampa television stations.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Comcast provides cable television service.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] DirecTV and Dish Network direct broadcast satellite television including Tampa Bay Area local and national channels to Sarasota residents.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Sarasota made national headlines in July 1974 when WWSB (then called WXLT) news anchor Christine Chubbuck shot herself live on-air.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Arbitron has identified the Sarasota-Bradenton radio market as the seventy-third largest market in the country, and the sixth largest in the state of Florida.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] WHPT (102.5 FM, Hot Talk) and WRUB (106.5FM, Spanish) are licensed to Sarasota and have broadcasting facilities in the Sarasota / Bradenton area, but have studios in the Tampa Bay area and are focused on that region.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] The community also is served by most radio stations from the Tampa Bay radio market, as well as some stations from the nearby Fort Myers radio market.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] The *Sarasota Herald-Tribune* is the daily newspaper published in the city and the weekly newspaper is the *Sarasota Observer*.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] From neighboring Manatee County, the *Bradenton Herald* also is distributed daily in the area and *The Bradenton Times* is an electronic weekly newspaper that covers Sarasota topics as well.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] *Sarasota Magazine* also served the community.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] DeMille filmed and premiered *The Greatest Show on Earth* (with James Stewart, Charlton Heston, Betty Hutton) in Sarasota.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] In 1998, two studio films were filmed in Sarasota: Alfonso Cuaron's *Great Expectations*, with Ethan Hawke, Gwyneth Paltrow, Hank Azaria, Anne Bancroft and Robert De Niro; and Volker Schlondorff's *Palmetto*, starring Woody Harrelson, Elisabeth Shue, and Gina Gershon.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] In June 2017, director Kevin Smith shot his 2022 film, *KillRoy Was Here*, in Sarasota.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] The major airport in the area is Sarasota–Bradenton International Airport (SRQ) which is shared by Sarasota and Manatee counties.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Since being opened in 1941, it has been the area's major airport.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Before this, Lowe's Field functioned as the main airport for the Sarasota Area from 1929 to 1941.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Five airlines offer service out of the airport to locations primarily in the United States and Canada.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] The airport serves more than 1,300,000 passengers per year.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] The airport holds full port of entry status providing U.S.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Customs inspections for international travelers.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Petersburg–Clearwater International Airport and Tampa International Airport are located about an hour north of Sarasota, and Southwest Florida International Airport in Ft.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Myers an hour and 45 min south of Sarasota.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] All three offer a wider range of national and international flights.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Sarasota County Area Transit has a bus service called *Breeze* which offers service throughout the county and also offers limited connections with Manatee County Area Transit.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Sarasota County has joined the Tampa Bay Area Regional Transportation Authority to plan and build future transportation infrastructure including light rail, commuter rail and longer range bus service.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] A key issue is providing Sarasota with access to the Florida High Speed Rail.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] The Seaboard Coast Line ran intercity train service to the city until 1971.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] There is no Amtrak train which stops in Sarasota, but Amtrak provides Amtrak Thruway at Sarasota Station, located approximately 2 miles (3.2 km) from the city limits of Sarasota, to the nearest Amtrak terminal in Tampa.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] A freight-only rail line operated by Seminole Gulf Railway does serve industries in Sarasota.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] The Seaboard Coast Line ran the last passenger train, the *West Coast Champion,* to the company's depot on 1971.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] As a city located on the Gulf of Mexico, water transportation is a key consideration.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] The Intracoastal Waterway is a 3,000-mile (4,800 km) waterway providing water access to and from the Atlantic coast for tugs, barges, and leisure boats.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Port Manatee and the Port of Tampa both provide nearby deep water ports.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Port Manatee provides cargo service primarily while the Port of Tampa is more diverse.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Port Manatee formerly even had a cruise line, *Regal Cruise Line* from 1993 to 2003.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] It was seized by U.S Marshals on April 18, 2003, for not being maintained.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] The waterway enters Sarasota Bay which provides access to downtown Sarasota at the city pier.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Because of its location on the Gulf of Mexico and its proximity to several other large metropolitan areas, road transportation is critical to the Sarasota area.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] The U.S. sister city program began in 1956 when President Dwight D.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] Eisenhower proposed a people-to-people, citizen diplomacy initiative.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] The Sarasota chapter was established in 1963.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] A sister city, county, or state relationship is a broad-based, long-term partnership between two communities in two countries.
[src:eliot-chapple/sarasota] A relationship is officially recognized after the highest elected or appointed official from both communities sign off on an agreement to become sister cities.
[src:eliot-chapple/society-for-applied-anthropology] The Society is unique among professional associations in membership and purpose – and in representing the interests of professionals in a wide range of settings including academia, business, law, public health, medicine, environment, and government.
[src:eliot-chapple/society-for-applied-anthropology] The unifying factor is a commitment to making an impact on the quality of life in the world.
[src:eliot-chapple/society-for-applied-anthropology] The Society publishes two journals: *Human Organization* and *Practicing Anthropology*.
[src:eliot-chapple/society-for-applied-anthropology] The SfAA was founded in 1941 and has maintained its status as an important resource for practicing and academic anthropologists alike.
[src:eliot-chapple/society-for-applied-anthropology] The SfAA consists of several special committees and interest groups that allow members to have meaningful dialog with other members from their specialized area of interest.
[src:eliot-chapple/society-for-applied-anthropology] The journals *Human Organization* and *Practicing Anthropology* are the best known of the SfAA's publications.
[src:eliot-chapple/society-for-applied-anthropology] The SfAA also publishes *The Classics of Practicing Anthropology;* *Human Rights: The Scholar as Activist - a special volume exploring how scholars can become advocates against human rights violations;* and a curated volume of essays honoring Malinowski Award recipients.
[src:eliot-chapple/society-for-applied-anthropology] The SfAA has an annual meeting every spring (March or April), usually in the US.
[src:eliot-chapple/society-for-applied-anthropology] Archived programs for meetings are available online back to 1999.
[src:eliot-chapple/society-for-applied-anthropology] The SfAA hosts its annual meeting with a number of co-sponsoring professional organizations that have similar goals.
[src:eliot-chapple/society-for-applied-anthropology] Some of these organizations include the Council on Nursing and Anthropology, the Society for Medical Anthropology, and the Political Ecoloty Society.
[src:eliot-chapple/society-for-applied-anthropology] Since 1973 the SfAA has awarded the Malinowski Award annually.
[src:eliot-chapple/society-for-applied-anthropology] The award is named in honor of famed anthropologist Bronislaw Malinowski.
[src:eliot-chapple/society-for-applied-anthropology] Malinowski was a leading advocate for the application of anthropological methods to address the world's problems.
[src:eliot-chapple/society-for-applied-anthropology] Malinowski argued that "anthropologists must advocate for native populations, involve themselves in policy matters and politics, and research contemporary social issues".
[src:eliot-chapple/society-for-applied-anthropology] The award is presented annually, beginning in 2002.
